<taxonomicName id="3CF784BEFFA5FF82FC62F91EFBF19EA1" authorityName="Nakai" authorityYear="1925" box="[919,1057,367,393]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Pleioblastus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="531" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C983232FFFA5FF82FC62F91EFBF19EA1" box="[919,1057,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">Pleioblastus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="3CF784BEFFA5FF82FBA1F91EFAF09EA1" authorityName="Makino" authorityYear="1914" box="[1108,1312,367,393]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Chimonobambusa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="531" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C983232FFFA5FF82FBA1F91EFAF09EA1" box="[1108,1312,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">Chimonobambusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(bamboos) (
<bibRefCitation id="9F6682CCFFA5FF82FF6AF9E2FE019E86" author="Garcia Morales, M. &amp; Denno, B. D. &amp; Miller, D. R. &amp; Miller, G. L. &amp; Ben-Dov, Y. &amp; Hardy, N. B." box="[159,465,403,430]" pageId="11" pageNumber="531" refId="ref4703" refString="Garcia Morales, M., Denno, B. D., Miller, D. R., Miller, G. L., Ben-Dov, Y. &amp; Hardy, N. B. (2016) ScaleNet: a literature-based model of scale insect biology and systematics. Database. Available from: http: // scalenet. info (accessed 25 November 2021)" type="url" year="2016">
García Morales 
<emphasis id="C983232FFFA5FF82FEA0F9E2FE569E85" box="[341,390,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB48FF3DFFA5FF82FF32F9C7FF3B9D31" blockId="11.[151,1437,151,646]" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">
<emphasis id="C983232FFFA5FF82FF32F9C7FEC39EF8" bold="true" box="[199,275,438,464]" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">Habit.</emphasis>
Females found on the lower leaf surfaces, at leaf bases, along the midrib, either individual or grouped close together; heavily infested leaves had wilted and developed black necrotic spots beneath and around the scale insects.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B3EDACB6FFA5FF82FF32FA52FC2D9DAE" pageId="11" pageNumber="531" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FB48FF3DFFA5FF82FF32FA52FC2D9DAE" blockId="11.[151,1437,151,646]" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">
<emphasis id="C983232FFFA5FF82FF32FA52FEEB9D15" bold="true" box="[199,315,547,573]" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="3CF784BEFFA5FF82FEBEFA52FD969D14" baseAuthorityName="Maskell" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[331,582,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Diaspididae" genus="Unachionaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="531" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="C983232FFFA5FF82FEBEFA52FD969D14" box="[331,582,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">Unachionaspis tenuis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName id="3CF784BEFFA5FF82FC2FFA52FB339D15" box="[986,1251,547,573]" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">
<emphasis id="C983232FFFA5FF82FC2FFA52FB529D15" box="[986,1154,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">Unachionaspis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by its unique, asymmetrical body shape, scattered dorsal microducts, and by each side having 2 marginal gland spines lateral to L 
<subScript id="6773FD78FFA5FF82FA61FA28FA4C9D4F" attach="left" box="[1428,1436,601,615]" fontSize="6" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">2</subScript>
(the other 
<taxonomicName id="3CF784BEFFA5FF82FEFFFA1AFDDA9DAD" box="[266,522,619,645]" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">
<emphasis id="C983232FFFA5FF82FEFFFA1AFE629DAD" box="[266,434,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="531">Unachionaspis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
all have only 1 gland spine in this position).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
